The most common natural disaster in the state of California is earthquakes. California is located along the Pacific Ring of Fire, which is a zone of frequent earthquake and volcanic activity. California experiences thousands of earthquakes each year, although most of them are too small to be felt. However, there have been many devastating earthquakes in California's history, including the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake, and the 1994 Northridge earthquake. Other natural disasters that occur in California include wildfires, floods, landslides, and droughts.